2025-12-10 23:35:29.732 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist0: Thought: The core challenge in few-shot learning lies in generalizing from minimal examples without overfitting or memorizing the training data. While generative adversarial networks (GANs) have been used to augment embeddings, they often fail to preserve class-discriminative structure or risk collapsing into mode duplication. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s probabilistic prototypes and uncertainty-aware representations, Paper 2’s use of semantic prompts to derive virtual class centers, and Paper 3’s emphasis on scalability in open-world settings, I propose a novel framework that reframes GAN-based embedding generation through *prototype-conditioned adversarial dynamics* in a structured latent space. Unlike prior methods that generate raw features or embeddings unconditionally or instance-wise, my idea introduces *semantic imagination*—a process where a generator learns to simulate plausible, diverse embeddings conditioned on distributional class prototypes derived from meta-knowledge, not just observed data. This avoids memorization by design, as the generator never sees real support examples during synthesis but instead imagines new embeddings based on high-level, abstracted class semantics. The adversarial loss is reformulated to enforce structural fidelity to prototype geometry rather than pixel- or feature-level realism, ensuring generated embeddings enhance discriminability. Crucially, prototypes are modeled as multivariate Gaussians (inspired by PRCL) to encode uncertainty and variance, enabling robustness to limited samples. Furthermore, unlike ConPVP, which uses prompts for sentence-level contrastive learning, this method integrates prompt-inspired semantic conditioning into a generative adversarial setup for visual or multimodal few-shot tasks. By decoupling generation from direct observation and anchoring it to probabilistic prototypes, PCLSA enables scalable, high-quality embedding augmentation that improves few-shot classification without overfitting—addressing a critical gap in open-world FSL highlighted in Paper 3.

